<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="prep-11-9">
  <title>Resources for 11/9</title>

  <objectives>
    <introduction>
      <p>For the content of this class, you will be expected to be able to do the following:</p>
    </introduction>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <p>
          Apply your understanding of exponential and logarithm functions to solve problems similar to half-life problems for exponential decay.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Apply your understanding of exponential and logarithm functions to solve problems similar to doubling time problems for exponential growth.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Use your understanding of exponential functions and logarithm functions to solve applied problems involving temperature of objects in an environment of constant temperature.
        </p>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </objectives>

  <subsection xml:id="video-activity-carbon-dating-2">
    <title>Video &amp; Activities for Carbon Dating and Doubling Time (Continued from Last Class)</title>
    <p>
      Below is a YouTube video on <em>carbon dating and doubling time</em>. It is followed by a link to a set of activities that we will be working on in class. Please watch the video and do as many of the activities as you can before class.
    </p>

    <video youtube="dUhWohuT6og" />

    <example>
      <title>Carbon Dating and Doubling Time</title>
      <p>
        For the following, justify any formulas you use that are not covered in class.
      </p>
      <p>
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              The half-life for carbon-14 is 5730 years.  A piece of once-living tissue is found to have 15% of its original carbon-14.  How long ago did the tissue die?
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              A population of insects grows exponentially.  Its doubling time is 15 days.  How long does it take for the population to quadruple?
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              In the tissue from #1, the same tissue had another isotope that is radioactive and had decayed to 40% of its original amount.  What is the half-life of the isotope?
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </example>
    <p>
      Feel free to post any questions you have on the <url href="">FigJam board</url> for the next class.
    </p>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="video-activity-logarithm-temperature">
    <title>Activities for Logarithms &amp; Temperature Problems</title>
    <p>
      Below is a set of activities on using logarithms on our <em>temperature models</em>.  in class. Please do as many of the activities as you can before class.
    </p>

    <example>
      <title>Using Logarithms to Solve Temperature Problems</title>
      <p>
        You put a warm object into a <m>40^\circ</m> refrigerator.  Initially, the object has a temperature of <m>75^\circ</m>.  After 10 minutes, the temperature has dropped to <m>60^\circ</m>.  For the following,  justify any formulas you use that are not covered in class.
      </p>
      <p>
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              Find a formula for the temperature <m>T(t)</m> of the object at time <m>t</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              What is the temperature of the object after 20 minutes?
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              How long will it take for the object to reach <m>47^\circ</m>?
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </example>
    <p>
      Feel free to post any questions you have on the <url href="">FigJam board</url> for the next class.
    </p>
  </subsection>

  <subsection>
    <title>Optional Reading</title>
    <p>
      Section 3.5: pp. 192-198
    </p>
    <p>
      Here is a link for the <url href="https://activecalculus.org/prelude/sec-exp-log-properties.html">HTML version of Section 3.5</url>.
    </p>
  </subsection>
</section>